<div id="review_2444590751" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2444590751" />
    <a title="Adrea Pierce" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24229097-adrea-pierce"><img alt="Adrea Pierce" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1380119920p2/24229097.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2444590751?book_show_action=true">Jul 03, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Adrea Pierce" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Adrea Pierce" href="/user/show/24229097-adrea-pierce">Adrea Pierce</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2444590751" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer248851292544167672">I began reading this book for two reasons. 1.) Because it fit the requirements of a challenge I’m in. 2.) Because it was there and I had enjoyed Shanghai Girls well enough. That said, I knew that this book revolved about Pearl and Joy and I just didn’t love either of them in the first book and because of this, I wasn’t in any rush to start this one. <br/><br/>Now that I have finished it, I would give this book 10 stars if I could. <br/><br/>It starts where Shanghai Girls ends. Joy has run away to Shanghai to find h</span>
  <span id="freeText248851292544167672" style="display:none">I began reading this book for two reasons. 1.) Because it fit the requirements of a challenge I’m in. 2.) Because it was there and I had enjoyed Shanghai Girls well enough. That said, I knew that this book revolved about Pearl and Joy and I just didn’t love either of them in the first book and because of this, I wasn’t in any rush to start this one. <br /><br />Now that I have finished it, I would give this book 10 stars if I could. <br /><br />It starts where Shanghai Girls ends. Joy has run away to Shanghai to find her birth father and Pearl, the mother who has raised Joy from birth follows her, knowing what Joy doesn’t...that they are embarking on an extremely dangerous journey. Joy is young and naive and Pearl is not. But the fierce love of a mother for her daughter has her following Joy despite the danger. The entire book centres around the Great Leap Forward and resulting famine in China’s history. <br /><br />This book was the most suspenseful book I’ve ever read, despite not being a suspense novel at all. From start to finish, my heart was in my throat. <br /><br />Lisa See was masterful in writing these two women. I went in to the book with lukewarm feelings towards them but I came to love them very quickly. See made these women come to life and feel like my own family. I truly cared what happened to them and more times than I can count, I found myself crying over their experiences. <br /><br />I do not want to give any spoilers, but I will say this. Be warned. This book takes place is an absolutely horrific period of China’s history. It is both beautifully written and incredibly hard to read. It is not for the weak of heart. This book will haunt me for years to come. </span>
  <a data-text-id="248851292544167672" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


